# API Test Checklist – GET /test-orders/auth

---

## Positive Test Cases

| #   | Test Description                           | Request Parameters                 | Expected Status | Notes                                   |
| --- | ------------------------------------------ | ---------------------------------- | --------------- | --------------------------------------- |
| 1   | Get order with correct username & password | `username=elena`, `password=elena` | 200             | Response body should contain order data |

---

## Negative Test Cases – Invalid Inputs

| #   | Test Description                  | Request Parameters                | Expected Status | Notes                                                                |
| --- | --------------------------------- | --------------------------------- | --------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| 2   | Get order with incorrect username | `username=123`, `password=elena`  | 400             | Actual API returned 200 – possible API/Swagger mismatch              |
| 3   | Get order with empty username     | `username= `, `password=elena`    | 400             | Actual API returned 200 – API accepts empty string as valid username |
| 4   | Get order with incorrect password | `username=elena`, `password=£@!$` | 400             | Actual API returned 200 – API does not validate special characters   |
| 5   | Get order without username        | `password=elena`                  | 500             | API crashed – server error                                           |
| 6   | Get order without password        | `username=elena`                  | 500             | API crashed – server error                                           |

---

## Notes / Observations

- Several negative tests fail because **API does not strictly validate inputs**.
- Requests without required parameters (`username` or `password`) return **500**, indicating **server-side error**.
- Log these as **documentation vs actual behavior discrepancies** for the team.

# API Test Checklist – PUT /test-orders

---

## Positive Test Cases – Update Order

| #   | Test Description                                  | Request Parameters       | Expected Status | Notes                                       |
| --- | ------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------ | --------------- | ------------------------------------------- |
| 1   | Update order with correct id=1 and valid api_key  | `id=1`, valid `api_key`  | 200             | Response body should reflect updated fields |
| 2   | Update order with correct id=2 and valid api_key  | `id=2`, valid `api_key`  | 200             | Response body should reflect updated fields |
| 3   | Update order with correct id=5 and valid api_key  | `id=5`, valid `api_key`  | 200             | Response body should reflect updated fields |
| 4   | Update order with correct id=9 and valid api_key  | `id=9`, valid `api_key`  | 200             | Response body should reflect updated fields |
| 5   | Update order with correct id=10 and valid api_key | `id=10`, valid `api_key` | 200             | Response body should reflect updated fields |

> 💡 Note: Positive tests can be simplified with a **loop over order IDs** instead of repeating code.

---

## Negative Test Cases – Invalid API Key or Body

| #   | Test Description                        | Request Parameters             | Expected Status | Notes                                                                                  |
| --- | --------------------------------------- | ------------------------------ | --------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| 1   | Update order with api_key not 16 digits | `id=2`, `api_key='1234567890'` | 401             | API should reject invalid key length                                                   |
| 2   | Update order with empty api_key         | `id=3`, `api_key=''`           | 401             | API should reject empty key                                                            |
| 3   | Update order with invalid api_key       | `id=3`, `api_key='abcd{£$'`    | 401             | API should reject invalid key format                                                   |
| 4   | Update order with missing api_key       | `id=3`, no `api_key`           | 401             | API should reject missing key                                                          |
| 5   | Update order with empty request body    | `id=3`, empty body `{}`        | 404             | According to docs, should return 404; actual API returned 200 – documentation mismatch |

---

## Notes / Observations

- Negative tests for invalid/missing API keys behave correctly (401).
- Test with empty request body fails (expected 404, got 200) – this should be logged as a **documentation discrepancy**.
- Positive tests could be **optimized using a loop over multiple IDs** to reduce repeated code.

# API Test Checklist – DELETE /test-orders

---

## Positive Test Cases – Delete Order

| #   | Test Description                               | Request Parameters      | Expected Status | Notes                                     |
| --- | ---------------------------------------------- | ----------------------- | --------------- | ----------------------------------------- |
| 1   | Delete order with correct id and valid api_key | `id=1`, valid `api_key` | 204             | No response body; order should be deleted |

---

## Negative Test Cases – Invalid or Missing API Key

| #   | Test Description                        | Request Parameters            | Expected Status | Notes                                     |
| --- | --------------------------------------- | ----------------------------- | --------------- | ----------------------------------------- |
| 1   | Delete order with missing api_key       | `id=2`, `api_key=''`          | 401             | API should reject missing key             |
| 2   | Delete order with invalid api_key       | `id=2`, `api_key='abcd{£$'`   | 401             | API should reject invalid key format      |
| 3   | Delete order with api_key not 16 digits | `id=3`, `api_key='123456789'` | 401             | API should reject key of incorrect length |

---

## Notes / Observations

- Positive test (204) returns **no body**, so do not attempt to parse JSON.
- Negative tests correctly return **401 Unauthorized** when api_key is invalid, missing, or wrong length.
- For completeness, after a successful DELETE, a **GET request for the same ID** can be used to confirm the order is removed (expect 404).
